ce:section.ce:para:
Fe3+ concentration-dependent fluorescence measurements of N-GQDs are illustrated in Fig. 10
                        , to further prove the feasibility of Fe3+ detection. The fluorescence intensity of N-GQDs decreases with an increase in the Fe3+ concentration (0–300 uM). Especially, the fluorescence intensity of N-GQDs linearly decreases with an increase in the Fe3+ concentration at 0–100 uM with a linear correlation of R2 = 0.98248(Fig. 10 (b))[63]. The calculated limit of detection is 0.74 uM (s = 0.43, S = 1.75), which is lower than the highest permissible value of Fe3+ in drinking water allowed by WHO (0.3 mg/L, i.e. 5.4 uM). Compared with the previously reported values (Table 1
                        ), the fluorescent probe based on N-GQDs possesses superior detection sensitivity.
